\label{def:dense-uniform}
A weighted bipartite graph $G \colon X \x Y \to [0,1]$ is said to satisfy the \emph{discrepancy} condition $\DISC(q,\epsilon)$ if
  \begin{equation} \label{eq:disc-dense}
    \abs{\int_{\substack{x \in X
        \\ y \in Y}} (G(x,y) - q) u(x) v(y) \ dxdy } \leq \epsilon
  \end{equation}
  for all functions $u \colon X \to [0,1]$ and $v \colon Y \to [0,1]$. In any weighted graph $G$, if $X$ and $Y$ are subsets of vertices of $G$, we say that the pair $(X, Y)_G$ satisfies $\DISC(q,  \epsilon)$ if the induced weighted graph on $X \x Y$ satisfies $\DISC(q,\epsilon)$.

